Walking Speed (10ft)

The 10-ft walking speed is measured every 6 months, 2 measurement were taken each time, and the average value is used for final analysis. 99 subjects has at least some walking speed records, while only 52 had more than 1 repeated measures, 23 from L group and 29 from S group.

Based on the estimated personal rate of changes, we can group the patients into the following three categories: 1. “No Change”: when estimated slope is not statistically significantly different from 0 (p.value > 0.05) 2. “Increase”: when estimated slope is statistically significantly greater than 0 (p.value <= 0.05) 3. “Decrease”: when estimated slope is statistically significantly less than 0 (p.value <= 0.05)

Table 2 - Walking Speed Change per Month

Increase,n(%) [miss] 11 (47.83%) [0] 9 (31.03%) [0]
No Change,n(%) [miss] 6 (26.09%) [0] 14 (48.28%) [0]

From the boxplots and summary table above, we observe: - There are no significant difference of Walking Speed change over time between two groups, however, the walking speed change is numerically more stable among the “Linguistic” group; - The walking speed change is a lot more variable among the the “Standard” group;due to such variability difference, we observe more extremely worse cases in the control (“Standard”) group

We further build a mixed effect model to better account for the nested variability structure, but still observed no significant difference in walking speed change between the two comparison groups.

Grip Strength

The grip strength was measured every 3 months, 2 measurements were taken each time, and the average value is used for final analysis. 142 subjects has at least some walking speed records, while only 110 had more than 2 repeated measures over time, 55 from L group and 55 from S group.

The “No change”, “Increase”, and “Decrease” groups are defined the similar way as above. By comparing the personalized rate of change for grip strength, we observed that there right grip strength reduced with a rate that is significantly slower than the standard group.

GaitRite Measurement

GaitRite metrics were collected every 6 months with 82 different metrics reported. 84 subjects has at least some walking speed records, while only 65 had more than 2 repeated measures over time, 30 from L group and 35 from S group.
